<div class="blog-faq">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How long after weight loss surgery should I wait before getting body contouring?</h3>
<p>Most surgeons recommend waiting at least 12 to 18 months after weight loss surgery before undergoing body contouring. This waiting period allows your weight to stabilize and ensures that your body has fully adjusted to its new shape. Dr. Johar will assess your readiness during your consultation and recommend the best time to proceed.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Can multiple body contouring procedures be performed at the same time?</h3>
<p>Yes, in many cases multiple procedures can be combined into a single surgical session. This approach reduces overall recovery time and may lower costs. However, combining procedures increases surgical complexity and duration, so Dr. Johar carefully evaluates each patient to determine whether combining procedures is safe and appropriate.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>What are the main risks of body contouring surgery?</h3>
<p>Risks include infection, bleeding, blood clots, scarring, asymmetry, numbness, and complications related to anesthesia. Choosing a board-certified and experienced plastic surgeon like Dr. Manoj K Johar significantly reduces these risks. Following post-operative instructions carefully also helps minimize complications and promote optimal healing.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Will I have visible scars after body contouring?</h3>
<p>Yes, body contouring procedures result in permanent scars. However, Dr. Johar places incisions in strategic locations that can be concealed by clothing. Over time, scars typically fade and become less noticeable with proper scar care, including sun protection and the use of scar treatment products.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How much weight do I need to lose before considering body contouring?</h3>
<p>Body contouring is not a weight loss procedure. It is designed for individuals who have already achieved significant weight loss and are at or near their ideal body weight. The amount of excess skin varies, but patients with 40 pounds or more of weight loss often benefit from body contouring procedures.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>When can I return to work after body contouring surgery?</h3>
<p>Most patients can return to desk jobs and light activities within two to four weeks after surgery. Strenuous physical activities and heavy lifting should be avoided for at least six to eight weeks. The exact timeline depends on the specific procedures performed and individual healing progress.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Will body contouring results last if I maintain my weight?</h3>
<p>Yes, body contouring results can last for many years with weight maintenance. The excess skin that is removed during surgery does not return. However, significant weight fluctuations after surgery can affect results, so maintaining a stable, healthy weight through diet and exercise is important for preserving your surgical outcome.</p>
</div>
</div>

